messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /api/users

All methods acceptable?
- allMethods: false

Per-method acceptability (based on the project code)
- HEAD: true
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- server.js mounts the user routes at the prefix /api/users via:
  app.use('/api/users', userRoutes);
- In routes/userRoutes.js the root of that router (router.route('/')) registers two handlers for the router root:
  - .post(registerUser) â€” this is the registerUser controller
  - .get(protect, admin, getUsers)
  Therefore the endpoint implemented by registerUser is POST /api/users, and there is also a GET /api/users handler (getUsers).
- Because the code does not use router.all(...) or app.all(...), allMethods is false.
- POST is true because registerUser is explicitly attached to POST on the router root.
- GET is true because getUsers is explicitly attached to GET on the same router root.
- HEAD is marked true because there is an explicit GET route for /api/users; Express provides HEAD responses for routes that have GET handlers (so a HEAD request will be handled by the existing GET route's headers behavior).
- OPTIONS is false: there is no explicit OPTIONS handler in the router or app, and no CORS/options middleware present in the provided code.
- TRACE is false: there is no TRACE handler registered.
- PUT, DELETE, PATCH are false for this exact path: PUT/DELETE/ PATCH handlers exist on other user-related paths (e.g., /api/users/:id and /api/users/profile) but not on /api/users itself.
